# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aerospace
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] An **accelerometer** is a device that measures the proper acceleration of an object.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Proper acceleration is the acceleration (the rate of change of velocity) of the object relative to an observer who is in free fall (that is, relative to an inertial frame of reference).
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Proper acceleration is different from coordinate acceleration, which is acceleration with respect to a given coordinate system, which may or may not be accelerating.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] For example, an accelerometer at rest on the surface of the Earth will measure an acceleration due to Earth's gravity straight upwards of about *g* ≈ 9.81 m/s2.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] By contrast, an accelerometer that is in free fall will measure zero acceleration.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Highly sensitive accelerometers are used in inertial navigation systems for aircraft and missiles.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] In unmanned aerial vehicles, accelerometers help to stabilize flight.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Micromachined micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS) accelerometers are used in handheld electronic devices such as smartphones, cameras and video-game controllers to detect movement and orientation of these devices.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Vibration in industrial machinery is monitored by accelerometers.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Seismometers are sensitive accelerometers for monitoring ground movement such as earthquakes.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] When two or more accelerometers are coordinated with one another, they can measure differences in proper acceleration, particularly gravity, over their separation in space—that is, the gradient of the gravitational field.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Gravity gradiometry is useful because absolute gravity is a weak effect and depends on the local density of the Earth, which is quite variable.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] A single-axis accelerometer measures acceleration along a specified axis.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] A multi-axis accelerometer detects both the magnitude and the direction of the proper acceleration, as a vector quantity, and is usually implemented as several single-axis accelerometers oriented along different axes.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] An accelerometer measures proper acceleration, which is the acceleration it experiences relative to freefall and is the acceleration felt by people and objects.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Put another way, at any point in spacetime the equivalence principle guarantees the existence of a local inertial frame, and an accelerometer measures the acceleration relative to that frame.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Such accelerations are popularly denoted g-force; i.e., in comparison to standard gravity.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] An accelerometer at rest relative to the Earth's surface will indicate approximately 1 g *upwards* because the Earth's surface exerts a normal force upwards relative to the local inertial frame (the frame of a freely falling object near the surface).
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] To obtain the acceleration due to motion with respect to the Earth, this "gravity offset" must be subtracted and corrections made for effects caused by the Earth's rotation relative to the inertial frame.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] The reason for the appearance of a gravitational offset is Einstein's equivalence principle, which states that the effects of gravity on an object are indistinguishable from acceleration.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] When held fixed in a gravitational field by, for example, applying a ground reaction force or an equivalent upward thrust, the reference frame for an accelerometer (its own casing) accelerates upwards with respect to a free-falling reference frame.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] For similar reasons, an accelerometer will read *zero* during any type of free fall.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] This includes use in a coasting spaceship in deep space far from any mass, a spaceship orbiting the Earth, an airplane in a parabolic "zero-g" arc, or any free-fall in a vacuum.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Another example is free-fall at a sufficiently high altitude that atmospheric effects can be neglected.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] However, this does not include a (non-free) fall in which air resistance produces drag forces that reduce the acceleration until constant terminal velocity is reached.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] At terminal velocity, the accelerometer will indicate 1 g acceleration upwards.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] For the same reason a skydiver, upon reaching terminal velocity, does not feel as though he or she were in "free-fall", but rather experiences a feeling similar to being supported (at 1 g) on a "bed" of uprushing air.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Acceleration is quantified in the SI unit metres per second per second (m/s2), in the cgs unit gal (Gal), or popularly in terms of standard gravity (*g*).
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] For the practical purpose of finding the acceleration of objects with respect to the Earth, such as for use in an inertial navigation system, a knowledge of local gravity is required.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] This can be obtained either by calibrating the device at rest, or from a known model of gravity at the approximate current position.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] A basic mechanical accelerometer is a damped proof mass on a spring.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] When the accelerometer experiences an acceleration, Newton's third law causes the spring's compression (or extension) to adjust to exert an equivalent force on the mass to counteract the acceleration.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Since the spring's force scales linearly with the length change (according to Hooke's law) and because the spring constant and mass are known constants, a measurement of the spring's compression (or extension) is also a measurement of acceleration.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] The system is damped to prevent oscillations of the mass and spring interfering with measurements.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] However, the damping causes accelerometers to have a frequency response.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Many animals have sensory organs to detect acceleration, especially gravity.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] In these, the proof mass is usually one or more crystals of calcium carbonate otoliths (Latin for "ear stone") or statoconia, acting against a bed of hairs connected to neurons.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] The hairs form the springs, with the neurons as sensors.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Many vertebrates, including humans, have these structures in their inner ears.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Most invertebrates have similar organs, but not as part of their hearing organs.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Mechanical accelerometers are often designed so that an electronic circuit senses a small amount of motion, then pushes on the proof mass with some type of linear motor to keep the proof mass from moving far.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] The motor might be an electromagnet or in very small accelerometers, electrostatic.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Since the circuit's electronic behavior can be carefully designed, and the proof mass does not move far, these designs can be very stable (i.e. they do not oscillate), very linear with a controlled frequency response.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] In mechanical accelerometers, measurement is often electrical, piezoelectric, piezoresistive or capacitive.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Piezoelectric accelerometers use piezoceramic sensors (e.g. lead zirconate titanate) or single crystals (e.g. quartz, tourmaline).
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] They are unmatched in high frequency measurements, low packaged weight, and resistance to high temperatures.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Piezoresistive accelerometers resist shock (very high accelerations) better.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Capacitive accelerometers typically use a silicon micro-machined sensing element.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Modern mechanical accelerometers are often small *micro-electro-mechanical systems* (MEMS), and are often very simple MEMS devices, consisting of little more than a cantilever beam with a proof mass (also known as *seismic mass*).
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Damping results from the residual gas sealed in the device.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] As long as the Q-factor is not too low, damping does not result in a lower sensitivity.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Under the influence of external accelerations, the proof mass deflects from its neutral position.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] This deflection is measured in an analog or digital manner.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Most commonly, the capacitance between a set of fixed beams and a set of beams attached to the proof mass is measured.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] This method is simple, reliable, and inexpensive.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Integrating piezoresistors in the springs to detect spring deformation, and thus deflection, is a good alternative, although a few more process steps are needed during the fabrication sequence.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] For very high sensitivities quantum tunnelling is also used; this requires a dedicated process making it very expensive.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Optical measurement has been demonstrated in laboratory devices.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Another MEMS-based accelerometer is a thermal (or convective) accelerometer.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] It contains a small heater in a very small dome.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] This heats the air or other fluid inside the dome.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] The thermal bubble acts as the proof mass.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] An accompanying temperature sensor (like a thermistor; or thermopile) in the dome measures the temperature in one location of the dome.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] This measures the location of the heated bubble within the dome.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] When the dome is accelerated, the colder, higher density fluid pushes the heated bubble.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] The temperature measurement is interpreted as acceleration.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Gravity acting on the fluid provides the spring.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Since the proof mass is very lightweight gas, and not held by a beam or lever, thermal accelerometers can survive high shocks.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Another variation uses a wire to both heat the gas and detect the change in temperature.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] The change of temperature changes the resistance of the wire.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] A two dimensional accelerometer can be economically constructed with one dome, one bubble and two measurement devices.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Most micromechanical accelerometers operate *in-plane*, that is, they are designed to be sensitive only to a direction in the plane of the die.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] By integrating two devices perpendicularly on a single die a two-axis accelerometer can be made.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] By adding another *out-of-plane* device, three axes can be measured.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Such a combination may have much lower misalignment error than three discrete models combined after packaging.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Micromechanical accelerometers are available in a wide variety of measuring ranges, reaching up to thousands of *g*'s.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] The designer must compromise between sensitivity and the maximum acceleration that can be measured.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Accelerometers can be used to measure vehicle acceleration.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Accelerometers can be used to measure vibration on cars, machines, buildings, process control systems and safety installations.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] They can also be used to measure seismic activity, inclination, machine vibration, dynamic distance and speed with or without the influence of gravity.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Applications for accelerometers that measure gravity, wherein an accelerometer is specifically configured for use in gravimetry, are called gravimeters.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also increasingly used in the biological sciences.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] High frequency recordings of bi-axial or tri-axial acceleration allows the discrimination of behavioral patterns while animals are out of sight.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] For example, accelerometers have been used to study flight energy expenditure of Harris's Hawk (*Parabuteo unicinctus*).
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Researchers are also using smartphone accelerometers to collect and extract mechano-biological descriptors of resistance exercise.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Increasingly, researchers are deploying accelerometers with additional technology, such as cameras or microphones, to better understand animal behaviour in the wild (for example, hunting behaviour of Canada lynx).
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also used for machinery health monitoring to report the vibration and its changes in time of shafts at the bearings of rotating equipment such as turbines, pumps, fans, rollers, compressors, or bearing fault which, if not attended to promptly, can lead to costly repairs.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Accelerometer vibration data allows the user to monitor machines and detect these faults before the rotating equipment fails completely.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Accelerometers are widely used in structural health monitoring (SHM) of buildings, bridges and other civil infrastructure to record the dynamic response under ambient and forced loads (e.g., wind, traffic, machinery and earthquakes).
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] From these vibration records, engineers estimate modal properties—natural frequencies, damping ratios and mode shapes—often using operational modal analysis (OMA) techniques for in-service structures.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] These parameters are trended over time for condition assessment and model updating.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] In seismic regions, arrays of accelerometers installed in buildings and other structures provide strong-motion data for rapid post-event assessments and long-term performance studies.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Geological Survey's National Strong-Motion Project (NSMP) operates structural arrays and distributes building and structural records via the Center for Engineering Strong Motion Data (CESMD).
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Instrumentation and data-quality practices for building vibration measurements are guided by international standards.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] ISO 4866 provides principles for measuring the vibration of fixed structures and evaluating vibration effects based on structural response, while ISO 10137 gives serviceability recommendations for buildings and walkways with respect to human perception, contents and the structure itself.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Choice of accelerometer technology depends on frequency range and amplitude.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Piezoelectric accelerometers are common for higher-frequency, higher-amplitude measurements, whereas low-noise MEMS accelerometers have become attractive for low-frequency building and bridge monitoring and for dense or wireless deployments due to cost and power advantages.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Recent evaluations and developments show that appropriately selected MEMS devices can identify modal parameters with acceptable accuracy for SHM and have been integrated into high-sensitivity wireless nodes.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Networked and wireless smart-sensor approaches allow distributed monitoring at scale.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Reviews document the shift from wired to wireless SHM systems and the maturation of wireless smart-sensor networks for tasks such as ambient-vibration modal identification and continuous trending.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Accelerometers are often fused with other sensors to improve displacement and drift estimation, especially for large or flexible structures.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] GNSS provides quasi-static and very-low-frequency motion that complements accelerometer-based dynamics; recent studies report accurate dynamic displacement retrieval using high-rate or multi-GNSS solutions combined with accelerometers.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Beyond permanently instrumented assets, indirect and crowdsourced approaches using smartphone accelerometers have been explored, particularly for bridges.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Research has shown that modal frequencies—and in some cases spatial vibration characteristics—can be estimated from accelerometer data collected by vehicles crossing bridges, offering a complementary, low-cost screening tool for large inventories.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Related work has also evaluated smartphone-based ambient vibration monitoring of buildings.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Long-term case studies illustrate large-scale deployments.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Hong Kong's Wind and Structural Health Monitoring System (WASHMS) has instrumented the Tsing Ma Bridge since 1997; subsequent publications report decades of monitoring for load and response in service.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Scotland's Queensferry Crossing was equipped with a comprehensive SHM system including thousands of sensors, and Sydney Harbour Bridge has been reported as instrumented with thousands of sensors for real-time monitoring.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] SHM data are used for continuous condition tracking, event-triggered assessments (e.g., after earthquakes), and to support asset management decisions.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] In bridge engineering, guidance from transportation agencies describes how field data—including accelerometer measurements—can be integrated with inspection and nondestructive evaluation to improve load-rating reliability and maintenance planning.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Zoll's AED Plus uses CPR-D•padz which contain an accelerometer to measure the depth of CPR chest compressions.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Within the last several years, several companies have produced and marketed sports watches for runners that include footpods, containing accelerometers to help determine the speed and distance for the runner wearing the unit.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] In Belgium, accelerometer-based step counters are promoted by the government to encourage people to walk a few thousand steps each day.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Herman Digital Trainer uses accelerometers to measure strike force in physical training.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] It has been suggested to build football helmets with accelerometers in order to measure the impact of head collisions.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] The US Army Research Laboratory developed the Three-Axis Acceleration Switch which has been suggested for this application.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Accelerometers have been used to calculate gait parameters, such as stance and swing phase.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] This kind of sensor can be used to measure or monitor people.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] An inertial navigation system is a navigation aid that uses a computer and motion sensors (accelerometers) to continuously calculate via dead reckoning the position, orientation, and velocity (direction and speed of movement) of a moving object without the need for external references.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Other terms used to refer to inertial navigation systems or closely related devices include inertial guidance system, inertial reference platform, and many other variations.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] An accelerometer alone is unsuitable to determine changes in altitude over distances where the vertical decrease of gravity is significant, such as for aircraft and rockets.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] In the presence of a gravitational gradient, the calibration and data reduction process is numerically unstable.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used to detect apogee in both professional and in amateur rocketry.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also being used in Intelligent Compaction rollers.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used alongside gyroscopes in inertial navigation systems.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] One of the most common uses for MEMS accelerometers is in airbag deployment systems for modern automobiles.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] In this case, the accelerometers are used to detect the rapid negative acceleration of the vehicle to determine when a collision has occurred and the severity of the collision.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Another common automotive use is in electronic stability control systems, which use a lateral accelerometer to measure cornering forces.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] The widespread use of accelerometers in the automotive industry has pushed their cost down dramatically.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Another automotive application is the monitoring of noise, vibration, and harshness (NVH), conditions that cause discomfort for drivers and passengers and may also be indicators of mechanical faults.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Tilting trains use accelerometers and gyroscopes to calculate the required tilt.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Modern electronic accelerometers are used in remote sensing devices intended for the monitoring of active volcanoes to detect the motion of magma.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Accelerometers are increasingly being incorporated into personal electronic devices to detect the orientation of the device, for example, a display screen.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] A *free-fall sensor* (FFS) is an accelerometer used to detect if a system has been dropped and is falling.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] It can then apply safety measures such as parking the head of a hard disk to prevent a head crash and resulting data loss upon impact.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] This device is included in the many common computer and consumer electronic products that are produced by a variety of manufacturers.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] It is also used in some data loggers to monitor handling operations for shipping containers.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] The length of time in free fall is used to calculate the height of drop and to estimate the shock to the package.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Some smartphones, digital audio players and personal digital assistants contain accelerometers for user interface control; often the accelerometer is used to present landscape or portrait views of the device's screen, based on the way the device is being held.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Apple has included an accelerometer in every generation of iPhone, iPad, and iPod touch, as well as in every iPod nano since the 4th generation.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Along with orientation view adjustment, accelerometers in mobile devices can also be used as pedometers, in conjunction with specialized applications.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Automatic Collision Notification (ACN) systems also use accelerometers in a system to call for help in event of a vehicle crash.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Prominent ACN systems include OnStar AACN service, Ford Link's 911 Assist, Toyota's Safety Connect, Lexus Link, or BMW Assist.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Many accelerometer-equipped smartphones also have ACN software available for download.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] ACN systems are activated by detecting crash-strength accelerations.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used in vehicle Electronic stability control systems to measure the vehicle's actual movement.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] A computer compares the vehicle's actual movement to the driver's steering and throttle input.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] The stability control computer can selectively brake individual wheels and/or reduce engine power to minimize the difference between driver input and the vehicle's actual movement.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] This can help prevent the vehicle from spinning or rolling over.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Some pedometers use an accelerometer to more accurately measure the number of steps taken and distance traveled than a mechanical sensor can provide.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Nintendo's Wii video game console uses a controller called a Wii Remote that contains a three-axis accelerometer and was designed primarily for motion input.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Users also have the option of buying an additional motion-sensitive attachment, the Nunchuk, so that motion input could be recorded from both of the user's hands independently.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Is also used on the Nintendo 3DS system.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Sleep phase alarm clocks use accelerometric sensors to detect movement of a sleeper, so that it can wake the person when he/she is not in REM phase, in order to awaken the person more easily.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] A microphone or eardrum is a membrane that responds to oscillations in air pressure.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] These oscillations cause acceleration, so accelerometers can be used to record sound.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] A 2012 study found that voices can be detected in 93% of typical daily situations by accelerometers like those in smartphones fixed to the sternum.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Conversely, carefully designed sounds can cause accelerometers to report false data.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] One study tested 20 models of (MEMS) smartphone accelerometers and found that a majority were susceptible to this attack.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] A number of 21st-century devices use accelerometers to align the screen depending on the direction the device is held (e.g., switching between portrait and landscape modes).
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Such devices include many tablet PCs and some smartphones and digital cameras.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] The Amida Simputer, a handheld Linux device launched in 2004, was the first commercial handheld to have a built-in accelerometer.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] It incorporated many gesture-based interactions using this accelerometer, including page-turning, zoom-in and zoom-out of images, change of portrait to landscape mode, and many simple gesture-based games.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] As of January 2009, almost all new mobile phones and digital cameras contain at least a tilt sensor and sometimes an accelerometer for the purpose of auto image rotation, motion-sensitive mini-games, and correcting shake when taking photographs.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Camcorders use accelerometers for image stabilization, either by moving optical elements to adjust the light path to the sensor to cancel out unintended motions or digitally shifting the image to smooth out detected motion.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Some stills cameras use accelerometers for anti-blur capturing.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] The camera holds off capturing the image when the camera is moving.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] When the camera is still (if only for a millisecond, as could be the case for vibration), the image is captured.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] An example of the application of this technology is the Glogger VS2, a phone application which runs on Symbian based phones with accelerometers such as the Nokia N96.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Some digital cameras contain accelerometers to determine the orientation of the photo being taken and also for rotating the current picture when viewing.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Many laptops feature an accelerometer which is used to detect drops.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] If a drop is detected, the heads of the hard disk are parked to avoid data loss and possible head or disk damage by the ensuing shock.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] A gravimeter, or gravitometer, is an instrument used in gravimetry for measuring the local gravitational field.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] A gravimeter is a type of accelerometer, except that accelerometers are susceptible to all vibrations including noise, that cause oscillatory accelerations.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] This is counteracted in the gravimeter by integral vibration isolation and signal processing.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Though the essential principle of design is the same as in accelerometers, gravimeters are typically designed to be much more sensitive than accelerometers in order to measure very tiny changes within the Earth's gravity, of 1 *g*.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] In contrast, other accelerometers are often designed to measure 1000 *g* or more, and many perform multi-axial measurements.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] The constraints on temporal resolution are usually less for gravimeters, so that resolution can be increased by processing the output with a longer "time constant".
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] If done without a user's knowledge or consent, this is referred to as an inference attack.
[src:aerospace/accelerometer] Additionally, millions of smartphones could be vulnerable to software cracking via accelerometers.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] Born in Lübeck, Germany, Busemann attended the Technical University of Braunschweig, receiving his Ph.D. in engineering in 1924.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] The next year he was given the position of aeronautical research scientist at the Max-Planck Institute where he joined the famed team led by Ludwig Prandtl, including Theodore von Kármán, Max Munk and Jakob Ackeret.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] In 1930 he was promoted to professor at University of Göttingen.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] He held various positions within the German scientific community during this period, and during the war he was the director of the Braunschweig Laboratory, a famous research establishment.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] Busemann discovered the benefits of the swept wing for aircraft at high speeds, presenting a paper on the topic at the Fifth Volta Conference in Rome on October 3, 1935, the very day of Italian invasion of Ethiopia which caused a delay of his talk.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] The paper concerned only supersonic lift.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] Nevertheless, he continued working with the concept, and by the end of the year had demonstrated similar benefits in the transonic region as well, after which the research topic was classified.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] As director of the Braunschweig labs, he started an experimental wind tunnel test series of the concept, and by 1942 had amassed a considerable amount of useful technical data.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] As the need for higher speed aircraft became pressing in Germany, the Messerschmitt Me P.1101 was developed to flight test these designs.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] When World War II ended, a team of American aerodynamicists travelled to Germany as part of Operation Lusty.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] The team included Theodore von Kármán, Tsien Hsue-shen, Hugh Dryden and George S.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] They reached the Braunschweig labs on 7 May, where they found a mass of data on the swept wing concept.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] When they asked Busemann about it, "his face lit up" and he said, "Oh, you remember, I read a paper on it at the Volta Conference in 1935".
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] Several members of the team did remember the presentation, but had completely forgotten the details in terms of what the presentation was actually about.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] Realizing its importance, Schairer immediately wrote to Boeing and told them to investigate the concept, leading to a re-modeling of the B-47 Stratojet with a swept wing.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] Busemann's work, along with similar work by Robert T.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] Jones in the US, led to a revolution in aircraft design.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] Near the end of the war, Busemann started studying airflow around delta wings, leading to the development of his supersonic conical flow theory.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] This reduced the complexity of the airflow to a conformal mapping in the complex plane, and was used for some time in the industry.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] Busemann moved to the United States in 1947 and started work at NACA's Langley Research Center.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] In 1951 he gave a talk where he described the fact that air at near supersonic speeds no longer varied in diameter with speed according to Bernoulli's theorem but remained largely incompressible and acting as fixed diameter pipes, or as he put it, 'streampipes'.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] He jokingly referred to aerodynamicists as needing to become 'pipe fitters'.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] This talk led an attendee, Richard Whitcomb, to try and work out what these pipes were doing in a transonic test he was performing, inventing the Whitcomb area rule a few days later.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] At Langley, he worked primarily on the problems of sonic booms, and spent a considerable amount of effort looking at ways to characterize them, and potentially eliminate them.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] He later invented Busemann's Biplane, a supersonic design he originally proposed in 1936 that emits no shock waves and has no wave drag, albeit at the cost of having no lift.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] Busemann also did early work on magneto-hydrodynamics in the 1920s, as well as on cylindrical focusing of shock waves and non-steady gas dynamics.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] Busemann held a professorship at the University of Colorado from 1963 and suggested the use of ceramic tiles on the Space Shuttle, which were adopted by NASA.
[src:aerospace/adolf-busemann] He was awarded the Ludwig-Prandtl-Ring from the Deutsche Gesellschaft für Luft- und Raumfahrt (German Society for Aeronautics and Astronautics) for "outstanding contribution in the field of aerospace engineering" in 1966.
[src:aerospace/aerodynamic-force] In fluid mechanics, an **aerodynamic force** is a force exerted on a body by the air (or other gas) in which the body is immersed, and is due to the relative motion between the body and the gas.
[src:aerospace/aerodynamic-force] Pressure acts normal to the surface, and shear force acts parallel to the surface.
[src:aerospace/aerodynamic-force] The net aerodynamic force on the body is equal to the pressure and shear forces integrated over the body's total exposed area.
[src:aerospace/aerodynamic-force] When an airfoil moves relative to the air, it generates an aerodynamic force determined by the velocity of relative motion, and the angle of attack.
[src:aerospace/aerodynamic-force] In addition to these two forces, the body may experience an aerodynamic moment.
[src:aerospace/aerodynamic-force] The force created by propellers and jet engines is called *thrust*, and is a reaction force.
[src:aerospace/aerodynamic-force] The other force acting on an aircraft is its weight, which is a body force and not an aerodynamic force.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] The border between space and the atmosphere has been proposed as 100 kilometres (62.1 mi) above the ground according to the physical explanation that the air density is too low for a lifting body to generate meaningful lift force without exceeding orbital velocity.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] This border has been called the Kármán line.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] In most industrial countries, the aerospace industry is a co-operation of the public and private sectors.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Along with these public space programs, many companies produce technical tools and components such as spacecraft and satellites.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Some known companies involved in space programs include Boeing, Cobham, Airbus, SpaceX, Lockheed Martin, RTX Corporation, MDA and Northrop Grumman.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] These companies are also involved in other areas of aerospace, such as the construction of aircraft.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Modern aerospace began with Engineer George Cayley in 1799.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Cayley proposed an aircraft with a "fixed wing and a horizontal and vertical tail," defining characteristics of the modern aeroplane.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] The 19th century saw the creation of the Aeronautical Society of Great Britain (1866), the American Rocketry Society, and the Institute of Aeronautical Sciences, all of which made aeronautics a more serious scientific discipline.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Airmen like Otto Lilienthal, who introduced cambered airfoils in 1891, used gliders to analyze aerodynamic forces.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] The Wright brothers were interested in Lilienthal's work and read several of his publications.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] They also found inspiration in Octave Chanute, an airman and the author of *Progress in Flying Machines* (1894).
[src:aerospace/aerospace] It was the preliminary work of Cayley, Lilienthal, Chanute, and other early aerospace engineers that brought about the first powered sustained flight at Kitty Hawk, North Carolina on December 17, 1903, by the Wright brothers.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] War and science fiction inspired scientists and engineers like Konstantin Tsiolkovsky and Wernher von Braun to achieve flight beyond the atmosphere.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] World War II inspired Wernher von Braun to create the V1 and V2 rockets.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] The launch of Sputnik 1 in October 1957 started the Space Age, and on July 20, 1969 Apollo 11 achieved the first crewed Moon landing.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] In April 1981, the Space Shuttle *Columbia* launched, the start of regular crewed access to orbital space.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] A sustained human presence in orbital space started with "Mir" in 1986 and is continued by the "International Space Station".
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Space commercialization and space tourism are more recent features of aerospace.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Aerospace manufacturing is a high-technology industry that produces "aircraft, guided missiles, space vehicles, aircraft engines, propulsion units, and related parts".
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Most of the industry is geared toward governmental work.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] For each original equipment manufacturer (OEM), the US government has assigned a Commercial and Government Entity (CAGE) code.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] These codes help to identify each manufacturer, repair facilities, and other critical aftermarket vendors in the aerospace industry.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] In the United States, the Department of Defense and the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) are the two largest consumers of aerospace technology and products.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Others include the very large airline industry.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] The aerospace industry employed 472,000 wage and salary workers in 2006.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Most of those jobs were in Washington state and in California, with Missouri, New York and Texas also being important.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] The leading aerospace manufacturers in the U.S. are Boeing, United Technologies Corporation, SpaceX, Northrop Grumman and Lockheed Martin.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] As talented American employees age and retire, these manufacturers face an expanding labor shortfall.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] In order to supply the industrial sector with fresh workers, apprenticeship programs like the Aerospace Joint Apprenticeship Council (AJAC) collaborate with community colleges and aerospace firms in Washington state.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] In the European Union, aerospace companies such as Airbus, Safran, Thales, Dassault Aviation, Leonardo and Saab AB account for a large share of the global aerospace industry and research effort, with the European Space Agency as one of the largest consumers of aerospace technology and products.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] In India, Bangalore is a major center of the aerospace industry, where Hindustan Aeronautics Limited, the National Aerospace Laboratories and the Indian Space Research Organisation are headquartered.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] The Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO) launched India's first Moon orbiter, Chandrayaan-1, in October 2008.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] In Russia, large aerospace companies like Oboronprom and the United Aircraft Building Corporation (encompassing Mikoyan, Sukhoi, Ilyushin, Tupolev, Yakovlev, and Irkut which includes Beriev) are among the major global players in this industry.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] The historic Soviet Union was also the home of a major aerospace industry.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] The United Kingdom attempted to maintain its own large aerospace industry, making its own airliners and warplanes, but it has largely turned to cooperative efforts with continental companies.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] It also imports from countries such as the United States.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] However, major companies such as BAE Systems supply fully assembled aircraft, aircraft components, sub-assemblies and sub-systems to other manufacturers, in Europe and other parts of the world.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Canada formerly manufactured some of its own designs for jet warplanes, etc.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] (e.g. the CF-100 fighter), but it has come to rely on imports from the United States and Europe to fill these needs.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] However Canada still manufactures some military aircraft.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Also notable is the late 1950s development of the Avro Canada CF-105 Arrow, a supersonic fighter-interceptor whose 1959 cancellation was controversial.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] France has continued to make its own warplanes for its air force and navy, and Sweden continues to make its own warplanes for the Swedish Air Force—especially in support of its position as a neutral country.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] (See Saab AB.) Other European countries either team up in making fighters (such as the Panavia Tornado and the Eurofighter Typhoon), or else to import them from the United States.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Pakistan has a developing aerospace engineering industry.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] The National Engineering and Scientific Commission, Khan Research Laboratories and Pakistan Aeronautical Complex are among the premier organizations involved in research and development in this sector.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Pakistan has the capability of designing and manufacturing guided rockets, missiles and space vehicles.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] The city of Kamra is home to the Pakistan Aeronautical Complex which contains several factories.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] This facility is responsible for manufacturing the MFI-17, MFI-395, K-8 and JF-17 Thunder aircraft.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Pakistan also has the capability to design and manufacture both armed and unarmed unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] In the People's Republic of China, Beijing, Xi'an, Chengdu, Shanghai, Shenyang and Nanchang are major research and manufacture centers of the aerospace industry.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] China has developed an extensive capability to design, test and produce military aircraft, missiles and space vehicles.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Despite the cancellation in 1983 of the experimental Shanghai Y-10, China is still developing its civil aerospace industry.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] The aircraft parts industry was born out of the sale of second-hand or used aircraft parts from the aerospace manufacture sector.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Within the United States there is a specific process that parts brokers or resellers must follow.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] This includes leveraging a certified repair station to overhaul and "tag" a part.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] This certification guarantees that a part was repaired or overhauled to meet OEM specifications.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Once a part is overhauled its value is determined from the supply and demand of the aerospace market.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] When an airline has an aircraft on the ground, the part that the airline requires to get the plane back into service becomes invaluable.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] This can drive the market for specific parts.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] There are several online marketplaces that assist with the commodity selling of aircraft parts.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] In the aerospace and defense industry, much consolidation occurred at the end of the 20th century and in the early 21st century.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Between 1988 and 2011, more than 6,068 mergers and acquisitions with a total known value of US$678 billion were announced worldwide.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Functional safety relates to a part of the general safety of a system or a piece of equipment.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] It implies that the system or equipment can be operated properly and without causing any danger, risk, damage or injury.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Functional safety is crucial in the aerospace industry, which allows no compromises or negligence.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] In this respect, supervisory bodies, such as the European Aviation Safety Agency, regulate the aerospace market with strict certification standards.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] This is meant to reach and ensure the highest possible level of safety.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] The standards AS 9100 in America, EN 9100 on the European market or JISQ 9100 in Asia particularly address the aerospace and aviation industry.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] These are standards applying to the functional safety of aerospace vehicles.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Some companies are therefore specialized in the certification, inspection, verification and testing of the vehicles and spare parts to ensure and attest compliance with the appropriate regulations.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] Spinoffs refer to any technology that is a direct result of coding or products created by NASA and redesigned for an alternate purpose.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] These technological advancements are one of the primary results of the aerospace industry, with $5.2 billion worth of revenue generated by spinoff technology, including computers and cellular devices.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] These spinoffs have applications in a variety of different fields including medicine, transportation, energy, consumer goods, public safety and more.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] NASA publishes an annual report called "Spinoffs", regarding many of the specific products and benefits to the aforementioned areas in an effort to highlight some of the ways funding is put to use.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] For example, in the most recent edition of this publication, "Spinoffs 2015", endoscopes are featured as one of the medical derivations of aerospace achievement.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] This device enables more precise and subsequently cost-effective neurosurgery by reducing complications through a minimally invasive procedure that abbreviates hospitalization.
[src:aerospace/aerospace] "These NASA technologies are not only giving companies and entrepreneurs a competitive edge in their own industries, but are also helping to shape budding industries, such as commercial lunar landers," said Daniel Lockney.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The **Hughes AIM-4 Falcon** was the first operational guided air-to-air missile of the United States Air Force.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] Development began in 1946; the weapon was first tested in 1949.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The missile entered service with the USAF in 1956.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] Produced in both infrared and radar-guided variants, the missile served during the Vietnam War with USAF McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II units.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] Designed to shoot down slow bombers with limited maneuverability, it was ineffective against maneuverable fighters over Vietnam.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] Lacking proximity fusing, the missile would detonate only on direct impact.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] With the AIM-4's poor kill record rendering the F-4D ineffective in air-to-air combat, the fighters were modified to carry the AIM-9 Sidewinder missile instead, which was already carried by USAF F-4Cs, USN and USMC F-4 Phantom II, and F-8 Crusader jet fighters.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The Sidewinder was more effective in the fighter vs fighter role on the F-4 platform, and improved versions continue to serve the armed forces of the United States and numerous nations to this day.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] Development of a guided air-to-air missile began in 1946.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] Hughes Aircraft was awarded a contract for a subsonic missile under the project designation **MX-798**, which soon gave way to the supersonic **MX-904** in 1947.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The original purpose of the weapon was as a self-defense weapon for bomber aircraft, which would carry a magazine of three missiles in the rear fuselage, and fire them through a long tube that led through the area that normally held the tail turret.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] In the case of the B-52, the missile contained a tuner for the bomber's A-3 rear-facing radar, and would follow the signal being reflected off the target aircraft using a semi-active radar homing (SARH) system.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] Soon after the original MX-798 was released, a specification for a forward-firing missile for fighter aircraft was issued which led to the MX-799.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] It advanced to testing prototype rounds, designated AAM-A-1 Firebird, but its subsonic speed and manual guidance soon proved to be serious problems.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The project was cancelled, and the recently released MX-904 was redirected to replace Firebird in the anti-bomber role.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] At this stage, the weapon was still designed to be fired out of a tube, now leading from a weapon bay behind the nose-mounted radar, with the launch tube exiting below the radar antenna.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] Instead of a magazine with multiple missiles, three missiles were placed in the tube tip-to-tail.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] Housing in a tube presented several problems, but primary among them was that there was no way for the missile's seeker to lock on before launch.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The original concept would be firing against interceptor aircraft that were slowly approaching the B-52 and would be somewhere fairly close to directly behind the aircraft.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] In the case of a fighter, the target might not be so conveniently located, and with no way to know if it could see the target while inside the tube, this meant it might never lock on properly.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] Eventually, it was decided to abandon the tube-launched concept and mount the missile on the wings or in weapon bays that would point the missile at the target prior to launch.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] This change also allowed the seeker to use infrared homing as well as SARH.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] Interchangeable seekers were developed, allowing an aircraft to carry either type, or both.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] Additionally, freed from the tube, the missile's wings were allowed to grow larger and took on the long delta form that it and its various descendants would carry into the 2000s.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The first test firings took place in 1949, at which time it was designated **AAM-A-2** and given the popular name **Falcon**.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] A brief policy of assigning fighter and bomber designations to missiles led it to be redesignated **F-98** in 1951.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] In 1955, the policy changed again, and the missile was again redesignated **GAR-1**.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The initial **GAR-1** and **GAR-2** models entered service in 1956.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] It armed the Northrop F-89 Scorpion, McDonnell F-101B Voodoo and Convair F-102 Delta Dagger and F-106 Delta Dart interceptors.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The only other users were Canada, Finland, Sweden and Switzerland, whose CF-101 Voodoo, Saab 35 Draken and Dassault Mirage IIIS carried the Falcon.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] Canada also hoped to use them on the Avro Canada CF-105 Arrow interceptor; however, this was never realized because of the Arrow's cancellation.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] Fighters carrying the Falcon were often designed with internal weapons bays for carrying this missile.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The Scorpion carried them on wingtip pods, while the Delta Dagger and Delta Dart had belly bays with a trapeze mechanism to move them into the airstream for launch.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The F-101B had an unusual bay arrangement where two were stored externally, and then the bay door would rotate to expose two more missiles.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] It is likely the General Dynamics F-111's internal bay would have accommodated the missile as well, but by the time of service the Air Force had already dropped the Falcon for use against fighters, as well as the idea of using the F-111 as an air combat fighter.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The GAR-1 had semi-active radar homing (SARH), giving a range of about 5 mi (8.0 km).
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] It was replaced in production by the **GAR-1D** (later **AIM-4A**), with larger control surfaces.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] About 12,000 of this variant were produced, the major production version of the SARH Falcon.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The **GAR-2** (later **AIM-4B**) was a heat-seeker, generally limited to rear-aspect engagements, but with the advantage of being a 'fire and forget' weapon.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] As would also be Soviet practice, it was common to fire the weapon in salvos of both types to increase the chances of a hit (a heat-seeking missile fired first, followed moments later by a radar-guided missile).
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The GAR-2 was about 1.5 in (40 mm) longer and 16 lb (7 kg) heavier than its SARH counterpart.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] It was replaced in production by the **GAR-2A** (later **AIM-4C**), with a more sensitive infrared seeker.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] A total of about 26,000 of the infrared-homing Falcons were built.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] All of the early Falcons had a small 7.6 lb (3.4 kg) warhead, limiting their lethal radius.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] Also limiting them tactically was that Falcon lacked a proximity fuze: the fuzing for the missile was in the leading edges of the wings, requiring a direct hit to detonate.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] In 1958, Hughes introduced a slightly enlarged version of the Falcon, initially dubbed **Super Falcon**, with a more powerful, longer-burning rocket engine, increasing speed and range.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] It had a larger warhead (28.7 lb / 13 kg) and better guidance systems.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] About 2,700 SARH missiles and 3,400 IR Super Falcons were produced, replacing most earlier versions of the weapon in service.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The Falcon was redesignated **AIM-4** in September 1962.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The final version of the original Falcon was the **GAR-2B** (later **AIM-4D**), which entered service in 1963.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] This was intended as a fighter combat weapon, combining the lighter, smaller airframe of the earlier GAR-1/GAR-2 weapon with the improved IR seeker of the GAR-4A/AIM-4G.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] An effort to address the limitations of AIM-4D led to the development in 1970 of the **XAIM-4H**, which had a laser proximity fuze, new warhead, and better maneuverability.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] It was cancelled the following year without entering service.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] A larger version of the Falcon carrying a 0.25-kiloton nuclear warhead was developed as the **GAR-11** (later designated the **AIM-26 Falcon**), while a long-range version was developed for the North American XF-108 Rapier and Lockheed YF-12 interceptors as the **GAR-9** (later **AIM-47 Falcon**).
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The Air Force deployed AIM-4 in May 1967 during the Vietnam War on the new F-4D Phantom II, which carried it on the inner wing pylons and was not wired to carry the AIM-9 Sidewinder.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The missile's combat performance was very poor.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The Falcon, already operational on Air Defense Command aircraft, was designed to be used against bombers, and its slow seeker cooling times (as much as six or seven seconds to obtain a lock on a target) rendered it largely ineffective against maneuvering fighters.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] Limited coolant supply meant that once cooled, the missile would expend its supply of liquid nitrogen in two minutes, rendering it useless on the rail.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The missile also had a small warhead, and lacked proximity fusing.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] As a result, only five kills were scored, all with the AIM-4D version.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The weapon was unpopular with pilots from the onset and was supplemented or partially withdrawn in 1969, to be replaced in the F-4D by the Sidewinder after retrofitting the proper wiring.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] Colonel Olds became exasperated with the Falcon's poor combat performance.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] He ordered his entire fighter wing to rewire the F-4Ds to carry more reliable AIM-9 Sidewinders.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] Although it was an unauthorized field modification, the entire air force eventually followed his example.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] Used from 1965 through 1972 in Vietnam, Falcons achieved their only kills during Operation Rolling Thunder (1965–68) , with only 5 successful hits scored after 54 launches in aerial combat.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The AIM-4 was also produced as the **HM-55S** (radar-guided) for the Swiss Air Force for use on the Dassault Mirage IIIS, and license-manufactured in Sweden for the Swedish Air Force (as the **Rb 28**) to equip the Saab 35 Draken and 37 Viggen.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The seeker of the missile was also redesigned.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] The AIM-4F/AIM-4G Super Falcon remained in USAF and ANG service, primarily with Convair F-102 Delta Dagger and F-106 Delta Dart interceptors, until the final retirement of the F-106 in 1988.
[src:aerospace/aim-4-falcon] These aircraft had been designed to carry the weapon and could not be easily converted to carry larger weapons like the AIM-9 Sidewinder or AIM-7 Sparrow, which were much longer.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] ARINC 429 is a data transfer standard for aircraft avionics.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] It uses a self-clocking, self-synchronizing data bus protocol (Tx and Rx are on separate ports).
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] The physical connection wires are twisted pairs carrying balanced differential signaling.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] Data words are 32 bits in length and most messages consist of a single data word.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] Messages are transmitted at either 12.5 or 100 kbit/s to other system elements that are monitoring the bus messages.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] The transmitter constantly transmits either 32-bit data words or the NULL state (0 Volts).
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] A single wire pair is limited to one transmitter and no more than 20 receivers.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] The protocol allows for self-clocking at the receiver end, thus eliminating the need to transmit clocking data.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] ARINC 429 is an alternative to MIL-STD-1553.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] The ARINC 429 unit of transmission is a fixed-length 32-bit frame, which the standard refers to as a 'word'.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] The bits within an ARINC 429 word are serially identified from Bit Number 1 to Bit Number 32 or simply Bit 1 to Bit 32.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] The fields and data structures of the ARINC 429 word are defined in terms of this numbering.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] While it is common to illustrate serial protocol frames progressing in time from right to left, a reversed ordering is commonly practiced within the ARINC standard.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] Even though ARINC 429 word transmission begins with Bit 1 and ends with Bit 32, it is common to diagram and describe ARINC 429 words in the order from Bit 32 to Bit 1.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] Generally, when the ARINC 429 word format is illustrated with Bit 32 to the left, the numeric representations in the data field are read with the most significant bit on the left.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] However, in this particular bit order presentation, the Label field reads with its most significant bit on the right.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] Like CAN Protocol Identifier Fields, ARINC 429 *label fields* are transmitted most significant bit first.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] However, like UART Protocol, Binary-coded decimal numbers and binary numbers in the ARINC 429 *data fields* are generally transmitted least significant bit first.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] The suppliers that use this representation have in effect renumbered the bits in the Label field, converting the standard's MSB 1 bit numbering for that field to LSB 1 bit numbering.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] This renumbering highlights the relative reversal of "bit endianness" between the Label representation and numeric data representations as defined within the ARINC 429 standard.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] Of note is how the *87654321* bit numbering is similar to the *76543210* bit numbering common in digital equipment; but reversed from the *12345678* bit numbering defined for the ARINC 429 Label field.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] This notional reversal also reflects historical implementation details.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] ARINC 429 transceivers have been implemented with 32-bit shift registers.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] Parallel access to that shift register is often octet-oriented.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] As such, the bit order of the octet access is the bit order of the accessing device, which is usually LSB 0; and serial transmission is arranged such that the least significant bit of each octet is transmitted first.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] So, in common practice, the accessing device wrote or read a "reversed label" (for example, to transmit a Label 2138 [or 8B16] the bit-reversed value D116 is written to the Label octet).
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] Newer or "enhanced" transceivers may be configured to reverse the Label field bit order "in hardware".
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] , and is used to verify that the word was not damaged or garbled during transmission.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] Every ARINC 429 channel typically uses "odd" parity - there must be an odd number of "1" bits in the word.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] This bit is set to 0 or 1 to ensure that the correct number of bits are set to 1 in the word.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] Normal Operation (NO) - Indicates the data in this word is considered to be correct data.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] Functional Test (FT) - Indicates that the data is being provided by a test source.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] Failure Warning (FW) - Indicates a failure which causes the data to be suspect or missing.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] No Computed Data (NCD) - Indicates that the data is missing or inaccurate for some reason other than a failure.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] For example, autopilot commands will show as NCD when the autopilot is not turned on.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] (BNR) are common ARINC 429 data formats.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] are Source/Destination Identifiers (SDI) and may indicate the intended receiver or, more frequently, indicate the transmitting subsystem.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] The image below exemplifies many of the concepts explained in the adjacent sections.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] In this image the Label (260) appears in red, the Data in blue-green and the Parity bit in navy blue.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] Label guidelines are provided as part of the ARINC 429 specification, for various equipment types.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] Each aircraft will contain a number of different systems, such as flight management computers, inertial reference systems, air data computers, radar altimeters, radios, and GPS sensors.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] For each type of equipment, a set of standard parameters is defined, which is common across all manufacturers and models.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] For example, any air data computer will provide the barometric altitude of the aircraft as label 203.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] This allows some degree of interchangeability of parts, as all air data computers behave, for the most part, in the same way.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] There are only a limited number of labels, though, and so label 203 may have some completely different meaning if sent by a GPS sensor, for example.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] Very commonly needed aircraft parameters, however, use the same label regardless of source.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] Also, as with any specification, each manufacturer has slight differences from the formal specification, such as by providing extra data above and beyond the specification, leaving out some data recommended by the specification, or other various changes.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] Avionics systems must meet environmental requirements, usually stated as RTCA DO-160 environmental categories.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] ARINC 429 employs several physical, electrical, and protocol techniques to minimize electromagnetic interference with on-board radios and other equipment, for example via other transmission cables.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] Its cabling is a shielded 78 Ω twisted-pair.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] ARINC signaling defines a 10 Vp differential between the Data A and Data B levels within the bipolar transmission (i.e.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] 5 V on Data A and -5 V on Data B would constitute a valid driving signal), and the specification defines acceptable voltage rise and fall times.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] ARINC 429's data encoding uses a complementary differential bipolar return-to-zero (BPRZ) transmission waveform, further reducing EMI emissions from the cable itself.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] When developing and/or troubleshooting the ARINC 429 bus, examination of hardware signals can be very important to find problems.
[src:aerospace/arinc-429] A protocol analyzer is useful to collect, analyze, decode and store signals.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] AS9100 replaces the earlier AS9000 and fully incorporates the entirety of the current version of ISO 9001, while adding requirements relating to quality and safety.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] Major aerospace manufacturers and suppliers worldwide require compliance with AS9100 as a condition of doing business with them.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] Prior to development of AS9100 standards for Quality Management Systems, the U.S. military applied two specifications to supplier quality and inspection programs, respectively, MIL-Q-9858A *Quality Program Requirements*, and MIL-I-45208A *Military Specification: Inspection System Requirements*.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] For years these specifications had represented the basic tenets of the aerospace industry.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] However, when the U.S. government adopted ISO 9001, it withdrew those two quality standards.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] Large aerospace companies then began requiring their suppliers to develop quality programs based on ISO 9001.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] As technologies evolve, and industries become more specialized, it is likely that more updates will be made to these standards and additional specialty Quality Management Systems (QMS) requirements for various industries.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] Prior to the adoption of an aerospace specific quality standard, various corporations typically used ISO 9001 and their own complementary quality documentation/requirements, such as Boeing's D1-9000 or the automotive Q standard.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] This created a patchwork of competing requirements that were difficult to enforce and/or comply with.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] The major American aerospace manufacturers collaborated to develop a unified quality standard based on ISO 9001:1994, which led to the creation of AS9000.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] Following its release, companies like Boeing discontinued their previous quality supplements in favor of complying with AS9000.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] Although AS9000 satisfied immediate needs, it was recognized that OEMs operate globally—a trend that would only increase, so a global standard was needed.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] The new standardized document, called 9100, was still based on ISO 9001:1994(E), although it was published separately by each country's aerospace association or standards body (AS9100 in the U.S).
[src:aerospace/as-9100] AS9100 added 55 aerospace industry specific amplifications and requirements to ISO 9001:1994.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] During the rewrite of ISO 9001 for the 2000 release, the AS group worked closely with the ISO organization.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] As the year 2000 revision of ISO 9001 incorporated major organizational and philosophical changes, AS9000 underwent a rewrite as well.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] It was released as AS9100 to the international aerospace industry at the same time as the new version of ISO 9001.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] AS9100A was actually two standards referenced in one publication: Section 1 defines an updated QMS model aligned with the updated ISO 9001:2000 publication while Section 2 defines a legacy model aligned with ISO 9001:1994.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] Organizations that in the year 2001 were operating a QMS based on ISO 9001:1994 were permitted to conform to Section 2 with the expectation that they would then transition their QMS to Section 1.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] As the period for transition from the 1994 to 2000 standards passed, AS9100B was released in 2004 as an administrative revision to delete Section 2 of the Revision A standard.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] Those organizations had documented controls that conformed to the standard, however, there were insufficient processes in place to assure effectiveness of those controls.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] The response in this AS9100 revision is to elevate the requirements for Risk Management and to make Risk Management an integrated theme throughout the standard.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] A major challenge to AS9100B-compliant organizations was the new AS9100 auditing standards defined in AS9101 Revision D, which eliminates the clause-based compliance checklist and requires organizations to provide evidence of effectiveness of their systems and processes.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] AS9100 Revision C was released in January, 2009, with considerable delay in application of the new version in audits, largely due to the delay in the release of AS9101 Revision D and auditor training to the increased auditing rigor of that update.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] The update of AS9100 from revision C to D includes the full text of ISO 9001:2015.
[src:aerospace/as-9100] AS9100 Revision D was released on September 20, 2016 with a certificate transition period aligned with the ISO 9001:2015 transition.
